but that's also what will make it not a successful desktop OS.

16:04.160 --> 16:05.160
So I'm curious.

16:05.160 --> 16:09.840
You got to compromise a little bit, it sounds like, to sometimes be ahead of the curve and

16:09.840 --> 16:12.120
try some new things that may or may not succeed.

16:12.120 --> 16:18.480
Wes, something you said that struck me here is there's so much more to Linux than the

16:18.480 --> 16:24.760
desktop, and a lot of people in our audience love Linux, think it's great, but they've

16:24.760 --> 16:29.280
decided to use Windows or Mac OS as their main desktop, and then they have a machine

16:29.280 --> 16:34.360
that they SSH into, and they spend so much time in that environment, it's where they

16:34.360 --> 16:41.640
spend the bulk of their passion project time is in a Linux environment, but they're connected

16:41.640 --> 16:45.320
from a Windows 10 or Mac box or something.

16:45.320 --> 16:50.320
And I think it's not a bad idea from time to time to take a break from the desktop and

16:50.320 --> 16:55.160
focus on the areas where Linux really kicks ass, and to figure out where that is, just

16:55.160 --> 16:56.160
follow the money.

16:56.160 --> 17:01.840
Linux is going to kick ass on the server because that's where a ton of money is, and the desktop

17:01.840 --> 17:07.760
is a passion project for a lot of people from a very skilled few who are generous enough

17:07.760 --> 17:13.040
with their time to make something as great as it is, but they don't have the benefit

17:13.040 --> 17:19.600
of Samsung, Intel, Western Digital and Google all contributing code to the same subsystem

17:19.600 --> 17:21.640
or something like that, right?

17:21.640 --> 17:25.760
Where the RISC-V people do have that kind of advantage, and it's because that's where

17:25.760 --> 17:31.240
the money is, and so I think there's absolutely nothing wrong with taking a bit of a break

17:31.240 --> 17:33.120
from time to time.

17:33.120 --> 17:37.040
Also, I consider myself a former Linux hype man.

17:37.040 --> 17:41.200
I still see a lot of people out there that do this, a lot of my friends, I used to be

17:41.200 --> 17:45.360
one of them, I mean that's what the Linux Action Show was, it was a lot of excitement

17:45.360 --> 17:46.360
and hype.

17:46.360 --> 17:48.280
I mean, remember that Switch to Linux challenge, anyone?

17:48.280 --> 17:50.800
Yeah, I was just gonna say that.

17:50.800 --> 17:57.660
Our mindset was everyone should be running Linux, and now my mindset is there's probably

17:57.660 --> 18:04.920
a distribution for everyone, but Linux itself is a power tool, and I know this is such an

18:04.920 --> 18:10.440
old tired analogy, but it is, really it holds up, otherwise it would probably have faded

18:10.440 --> 18:16.880
by now, but you don't recommend that people commute to work in trucks or run their errands

18:16.880 --> 18:18.400
in a truck.

18:18.400 --> 18:23.800
A truck is something that has capacity for work, it's something you use as a work vehicle,

18:23.800 --> 18:27.340
and it's not a vehicle for every day, every one.

18:27.340 --> 18:32.160
It is appropriate for some, and we don't sit here and try to sell trucks to everybody all

18:32.160 --> 18:37.560
day long, but when you just come in with this hype that Linux is for everyone and that you

18:37.560 --> 18:41.980
should be able to do a one-to-one swap from your Windows machine to Linux, we're selling

18:41.980 --> 18:46.840
a false hope, and every now and then, we manage to sell that false hope to somebody who has

18:46.840 --> 18:52.920
like a large YouTube channel, and then they go on there, and they call dolphin shit, and

18:52.920 --> 18:59.080
they crap on free software efforts, because they're looking at it with a completely distorted

18:59.080 --> 19:03.600
perspective, and maybe one day we could say, yes, it's a one-for-one swap for everybody,

19:03.600 --> 19:04.720
but that's not it.

19:04.720 --> 19:08.800
So take a break, focus on the stuff that does kick ass, and then what you'll find when you

19:08.800 --> 19:13.440
come back in, you'll be really impressed and enthusiastic about the improvements in the

19:13.440 --> 19:18.160
Linux desktop, because it always does keep improving, and so when you take a bit of a

19:18.160 --> 19:23.680
break, even a few months, and come back, it's like, wow, look what they've done, and it's

19:23.680 --> 19:24.680
fun again.

19:24.680 --> 19:27.280
Hey, I like that approach, you know, focusing on the fun parts.

19:27.280 --> 19:28.600
You don't have to force it.

19:28.600 --> 19:30.280
If it's not working, there's no shame in that.

19:30.280 --> 19:35.080
I think maybe sometimes we attach a little bit too much hype and focus and just, I mean,

19:35.080 --> 19:38.660
I think we all would love to live in a world where the first-class premium desktop experience

19:38.660 --> 19:43.480
was also free software, but if that's not the case, you know, we can still hope for

19:43.480 --> 19:48.040
better things, we can still admire the progress we get, and then also just acknowledge the

19:48.040 --> 19:49.940
state of where things are and be okay with that.

19:49.940 --> 19:55.960
I don't think it's inappropriate at all to think of Linux as a raw material from which

19:55.960 --> 20:01.520
