20:05.880 --> 20:08.780
that we don't even think of it as that anymore.

20:08.780 --> 20:15.160
But if you look at where Linux has been massively successful amongst average users, it's when

20:15.160 --> 20:21.080
a company or a group has come along and taken the stack, they've made selective choices

20:21.080 --> 20:26.400
about what's in that stack, they've curated it, and they've created a product out of it.

20:26.400 --> 20:29.880
Look at Chrome OS, look at Android, and now look at the Steam Deck.

20:29.880 --> 20:32.120
The Steam Deck is a curated product.

20:32.120 --> 20:37.560
Again, they took special effort into making a curated thing from these raw materials,

20:37.560 --> 20:40.520
and that's what we're really doing with our own desktops, we just don't even really realize

20:40.520 --> 20:41.520
it.

20:41.520 --> 20:47.000
And the end users that have come from something like Mac OS or Windows or Chrome OS, they're

20:47.000 --> 20:48.880
not thinking about it in those terms.

